  "prompt": "Which day can be the first and the last day of a century?",
  "response": "To find out which day can be the **first and last day of a century**, we need to understand how the calendar cycles work, particularly focusing on **leap years** and the **Gregorian calendar** which is the most widely used civil calendar today.\n\n### Step 1: Understanding Leap Years\nA **leap year** occurs every 4 years to account for the extra ~0.25 days it takes Earth to orbit the Sun. However, there are exceptions:\n- **Century Rule:** If you have a year divisible by 100, it is **not** a leap year unless it's also divisible by 400.\n\nThis means:\n- **1700, 1800, 1900** were **not** leap years.\n- **1600, 2000** were leap years.\n\n### Step 2: Calculating the Number of Leap Years in a Century\nTo find the total number of days in a century:\n1. **Basic Length:** 100 years \u00d7 365 days/year = 36,500 days\n2. **Leap Year Adjustment:**  \n   - Typically, every 4th year is a leap year: 100 \u00f7 4 = **25 leap years**  \n   - Subtract the century years that are not leap years (most centuries): 25 - 1 = **24 leap years**\n\nHowever, if the century year itself is a leap year (e.g., 2000), there are **25 leap years**.\n\n### Step 3: Total Days in a Century\nFor most centuries:\n- Total days = 36,500 + 24 = **36,524 days**\n\nFor centuries like 2000:\n- Total days = 36,500 + 25 = **36,525 days**\n\n### Step 4: Determining the Day of the Week\nSince days of the week cycle every **7 days**, we find the remainder when dividing the total days by 7.\n\n1. **For Most Centuries (24 leap years):**\n   - 36,524 \u00f7 7 = 5,217 weeks with a remainder of **5 days**\n   \n2. **For Leap Century (25 leap years):**\n   - 36,525 \u00f7 7 = 5,217 weeks with a remainder of **6 days**\n\n**Interpretation:**\n- Starting from a specific day, adding the remainder will give the day of the week for the last day of the century.\n\n### Step 5: Establishing the Starting Points\nAssuming a given day for the first day allows us to determine the last day.\n\nFor example:\n- **If a century starts on Monday:**\n  - Most centuries will end on **Saturday** (Monday + 5 days)\n  - Leap centuries will end on **Sunday** (Monday + 6 days)\n\nHowever, history shows a specific pattern due to the Gregorian calendar's rules.\n\n### Step 6: Historical Observation\nFrom historical records:\n- The **20th century (1901-2000)** started on a **Tuesday** and ended on a **Monday** (as 1900 was **not** a leap year, so there were 24 leap years).\n- The **21st century (2001-2100)** started on a **Monday** and will end on a **Sunday** (as 2000 was a leap year, ending with 25 leap years).\n\n### Step 7: Identifying Possible Days\nBased on the above, the days for the **first** and **last** day of a century can be mapped as follows:\n\n- **If the century starts on a Monday:**\n  - Ends on **Sunday** (leap century)\n- **If the century starts on a Tuesday:**\n  - Ends on **Monday**\n- **If the century starts on a Wednesday:**\n  - Ends on **Tuesday**\n- **If the century starts on a Thursday:**\n  - Ends on **Wednesday**\n- **If the century starts on a Friday:**\n  - Ends on **Thursday**\n- **If the century starts on a Saturday:**\n  - Ends on **Friday**\n- **If the century starts on a Sunday:**\n  - Ends on **Saturday**\n\nHowever, due to the Gregorian calendar rules, **only certain pairs** happen in reality.\n\n### Final Answer\n**A century can start and end on the following days:**\n- **Starts on Monday** and **ends on Sunday**\n- **Starts on Tuesday** and **ends on Monday**\n- **Starts on Wednesday** and **ends on Tuesday**\n- **Starts on Thursday** and **ends on Wednesday**\n- **Starts on Friday** and **ends on Thursday**\n- **Starts on Saturday** and **ends on Friday**\n- **Starts on Sunday** and **ends on Saturday**\n\nBut considering the Gregorian calendar's leap year rules, **each century consistently shifts the starting day by one day for non-leap centuries and two days for leap centuries**. This cyclical pattern ensures that over time, every day of the week can serve as both the first and last day of a century. \n\nTherefore, **any day in the week (Monday through Sunday)** can be both the **first and last day of a century**, depending on the century's starting point and the number of leap years it contains.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
